<p>Explore the authentic culture and beautiful backwaters of Kerala, which is blessed to be named God&rsquo;s Own Country, has both stunning scenic beauty and cultural heritage. Famous for its serene beaches, swaying with coconut trees and mesmeric hill station, is a perfect destination for a relaxing vacation trip.</p>

<p>We offer top notch travel services with quick customer support so that you can enjoy your vacation. Browse through our Kerala tour packages and choose your ideal Kerala packages to explore the land rich of culture and natural beauty.</p>

<h2>Best Time to visit Kerala</h2>
<p>September to March are the best time to visit Kerala. This is the season when Kerala's climate is comfortable and pleasant. With less humidity, you can easily stroll outside and explore God&rsquo;s own place.</p>

<h2>How to reach Kerala</h2>

<p><strong>By Air</strong>- The state has four international airports, Thiruvananthapuram International Airport, Kochi International Airport, Kozhikode International Airport, and Kannur International Airport. You can easily get flights to any of them.</p>

<p><strong>By Train</strong>- Several trains connect to Kerala from many prominent cities. Take train from your hometown to Kerala and reach Thiruvananthapuram Central Station (TVC)</p>

<p><strong>By Road</strong>- Even if travelling by car to Kerala is a possibility, it is quite time-consuming. It is ideal for travellers planning a Kerala vacation from a nearby state or those seeking a spectacular road trip.</p>

<h2>Best Places to Visit in Kerala</h2>

<h3>Eravikulam National Park in Kerala</h3>
<p>Eravikulam National Park, located barely 12 km from Munnar, is one of Kerala's most beautiful destinations. In addition to its stunning splendour, this national park is home to Nilgiri tahr, lion-tailed macaques, wild dogs, jungle cats, leopards, and other wildlife.</p>
<h3>Mattancherry Palace in Kerala</h3>
<p>The Mattancherry Palace, also known as the Dutch Palace, is a palace situated in Mattancherry, Kochi, in the Indian state of Kerala. Built in 1545 by the Portuguese as a gift to the king of Cochin, it was later renovated by the Dutch in 1663. Book Kerala tour packages with invisit.</p>
<h3>Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary in Kerala</h3>
<p>The Periyar Wildlife Sanctuary, also known as the Periyar Tiger Reserve, is a protected area located in the mountainous Western Ghats of Kerala, southern India. Established in 1982, it is one of the most popular wildlife sanctuaries in India .</p>
<h3>Varkala Beach in Kerala</h3>
<p>If you're searching for a pleasant beach experience on your trip to Kerala, make sure to stop at Varkala Beach. Located in Varkala Town, Thiruvananthapuram district, this gorgeous length of golden sand will provide visitors with some of the greatest picturesque vistas in the area.</p>
<h3>Alleppey in Kerala</h3>
<p>Alleppey, formally named Alappuzha, is one of Kerala's most attractive tourist destinations. It is home to various tourist sites, including Alappuzha Beach, the Alappuzha Lighthouse, the Sree Krishna Temple, and St. Mary's Forane Church. The most prominent feature of Alleppey is its extensive network of interconnecting canals and backwaters.</p>
<h3>Cochin in Kerala</h3>
<p>Kochi, commonly known as Cochin, is one of Kerala's most breathtaking tourist destinations in India. It is a famous tourist destination due to its scenic environment, natural beauty, and historical and cultural value. Fort Kochi, Santa Cruz Cathedral Basilica, Kerala Folklore Museum, Mattancherru Palace, Hill Palace Museum, and other sites are popular among tourists.</p>
<h3>Thekkady in Kerala</h3>
<p>Thekkady is one of Kerala's top tourist destinations, where you can spend a few days in the tranquilly and beauty of nature. It suits the mood of a relaxing holiday and has lush vegetation, tea and coffee plantations, waterfalls, mountains, rivers, and so on. Tourists visiting Thekkady may also participate in a variety of enjoyable activities, including as bird viewing, jungle safaris, trekking, and rafting.</p>
<h3>Thrissur in Kerala</h3>
<p>Thrissur is known as Kerala's Cultural Capital because of its strong religious, spiritual, and cultural origins. Tourists from all over India and the world come to this city to celebrate the famed festivals of Thrissur Pooram and Onam. Aside from these, it is home to a number of notable tourist sites, including Shakthan Thampuran Palace, Thrissur Zoo, Athirapally Falls, Charpa Falls, and Vadakummanathan Temple.</p>
<h3>Kozhikode in Kerala</h3>
<p>Kozhikode, often known as Calicut, is one of the greatest Kerala tourism destinations for solitary travellers. For hundreds of years, it was Malabar's capital and an important commercial city. It is now a major tourist destination, including prominent sites like as the Pazhassi Raja Museum and Art Gallery, Kozhikode Beach, Thikkoti Light House, Thali Temple, and so on.</p>
<h3>Munnar in Kerala</h3>
<p>Munnar is a beautiful hill station located in the Idukki district of Kerala, India. Often referred to as the &quot;Kashmir of South India&quot;, Munnar is known for its stunning natural beauty, rolling hills covered in lush green tea plantations, misty mountains, and cool climate</p>
<h3>Kochi in Kerala</h3>
<p>A vacation to Kerala isn't complete without seeing Kochi, the state's cultural hub. Where you will find a rich combination of history, great architecture, nature in all its grandeur, a thriving culinary scene, historical arts and crafts, and gorgeous spiritual sites—a heady mix of everything that makes travel so fascinating.</p>
<h3>Kovalam in Kerala</h3>
<p>The immaculate crescent-shaped coastal stretch of Kovalam consists of three beaches: Lighthouse, Hawah, and Samudra. Each of them has its own unique way of leaving you completely captivated by the picture-perfect tropical atmosphere. Golden sands, exciting water sports, swaying palm trees to hammock under, and isolated stretches with views reserved just for you.</p>

